@book{richardsonSystemsApproachesManaging2016,
  title = {Systems {{Approaches}} to {{Managing Change}}: {{A Practical Guide}}},
  author = {Richardson, Neil},
  date = {2016},
  volume = {15},
  abstract = {SODA, SSM, CSH and SD are hardly trendy acronyms; even among practicing managers they won't enjoy widespread recognition. Authors Reynolds and Holwell explain the novel termi-nology points to radical approaches in organisational research: participative ways of interven-ing in complex dilemmas troubled by uncertainty. These approaches are therefore not techniques for solving easily-defined problems but are means for tackling social 'messes'. If social problem X is opaque, awkward to express in words, then the interesting modes of research discussed in this book might be a good idea. The group or advisor troubled by X would choose an approach which seems easy to understand and put to work, perhaps one that can be used again after an itinerant consultancy team has moved on. Yet this line of thought puts a huge burden on the approach architect: to draft principles amenable to multifarious men and women -whatever their histories, ambition and foibles – and which also help make sense of fuzzy, never-to-be-repeated organisational dilemmas. Occasionally the writing in SAMC strays too far from lay readers' backgrounds, people who ought to be kept on-board if participation is sought. Although the first chapter shows how research principles have been grouped together by several authors, the categorising can be controversial; for instance, in figure 1.2 the work of Jackson, Ulrich, and Flood points towards a bubble labelled critical systems, while Open University and Checkland points to a very general label of applied systems studies rather than his innovation SSM or the phrase soft systems, an unusual slant. In chapter two Dr John Morecroft describes Systems Dynamics, an approach linked to Jay Forrester's research and The Fifth Discipline of Peter Senge. Examples of mixing hot and cold flows in a shower (with annoying time delays) and the relation between hunger and food give the gist of Systems Dynamics, before complex settings of drug related crime Philosophy of Management (2016) 15:251–254 and airline marketing. An arrow which links Hunger with Amount Eaten is shown as positive – with another counteracting effect (negative) from Amount Eaten to Hunger, thus appetites are balanced. However, it may be that habit, stress or flavourings keep Joe eating well beyond a recommended balance. Another contrary notion is whether an increase in the number of police allocated to drug busting will increase drug seizures (figure 2.19) when wise guys in that trade learn from their mistakes. The mathematical nature of SD – including skill in 'writing good algebra' with 'equations that mean what you intend' -appears on computer simulators, putting this programme beyond the budget of many organisations and into the hands of consultants. Even a thousand lines of their expert algebra will capture neither how reality 'actually is' nor tomorrow's insights for change. Patrick Hoverstadt briefs readers on the Virtual System Model in chapter three, reliant on the texts of Stafford Beer and his 'laws of viable organisation'. Deploying five sub-systems and a principle of recursion, Beer's VSM model allows comparisons against real organisations. As examples of system descriptions, S2 is a sub-system of activities which stop different operations causing problems for one another, while S5 is comprised of management activities which ensure the organisation works as a system. Does the generality of S5 make S2 redundant? No methodology is required here, an omission which might puzzle those unfamil-iar with organisational research. One principle is stressed: Only variety can absorb variety. Figure 3.3 (Balancing the complexity equation) shows how an organisation (presumably its executives) reduces variety of the environment into market segments, subsequently reduced by management into divisions which handle complex tasks. Management and the organisation can also amplify their own variety, for instance by 'increasing divisional autonomy'. This so called 'balancing act' might be translated into the modest claim that various groups at various times will do their best to satisfy events and trends, no algebraic dexterity required, and not a simultaneous equation in sight. Chapter four's SODA (Strategic Options and Analysis) by Fran Ackermann and Colin Eden can explore options within tricky situations via a means-ends network, supported where necessary by causal mapping software and based on theories from cognitive psychology and social negotiation. In general, moving from the top to bottom of these networks we first encounter consequences and objectives above a central issue, then, at the diagram's base are constraints and options. Since the authors advise working with multiple perspectives and construe events differently, they may allow doubts about their Process \& Content diagram (Figure 4.2). Instead of aligning Process with 'power, skills and personalities' and Content with 'capturing and analysing data and analysing problem statements' – the labels make more sense when flipped: the content of a study would include a note on the power, skills and personalities encountered within the client organisation. With SODA exercises collecting up to sixty statements during forty-five minutes of discussion and the need for the computer-based tool Decision Explorer when models become large, this systems approach is another requiring expert input. Bewitched by language? A simple string of words might trouble newcomers. For instance, figure 4.7 includes three linked phrases,},
